{{italic title}} [[File:Kejimkujik_NP_Nova_Scotia_3.jpg|right|thumb|300px|The point which today beats his name within the boundaries of [[Kejimkujik National Park]] which was the inspiration for the novel]] '''''John Paul's Rock''''' is a [[novel]] published in 1932 by Canadian writer [[Frank Parker Day]], about a [[Mi'kmaq]] guide who fled into Nova Scotia to escape white man's law.<ref>"Nova Scotia Tragedy". ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'', August 20, 1932.</ref>
==Overview== Minton, Balch & Company, New York, 1932. Hardcover.
==Inspiration== Jim Charles, who was the inspiration for the novel, was perhaps the most noted Indian guide in both fact and fiction. His notoriety comes not from his guiding expertise but from his discovery of gold and a subsequent brush with the law which led to his fleeing as a fugitive into the wilds of the interior. In the 1860s he was living in a cabin and tending a few heads of cattle and a horse on the point which today beats his name within the boundaries of [[Kejimkujik National Park]].<ref>{{cite book | first = Mike | last = Parker | year = 1990 | title = Guides of the North Woods | publisher = Numbus Publishing Limited | isbn = 0-921054-37-8}}</ref>
