{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}} {{Use Indian English|date=May 2018}} {{ infobox theatre group | name = Swapnasandhani | image = Swapnasandhani Bengali theatre group logo.jpg | imagesize = 150px | caption = Swapnasandhani group logo | ArtisticDirector = [[Kaushik Sen]] | formed = 29 May 1992<ref name="wordpress1">{{cite web|title=Article on Swapnasandhani|url=http://banglatheatre.wordpress.com/2010/10/25/swapnasandhani/}}</ref> | location = [[Kolkata]], [[West Bengal]], [[India]] | disbanded = | members = [[Kaushik Sen]], [[Chitra Sen]], Reshmi Sen, Dwitipriya, Rabindranath Jana, [[Riddhi Sen]] | notable = | homepage = | genre = }}
'''Swapnasandhani''' ([[Bengali language|Bengali]]: {{audio|Bn-স্বপ্নসন্ধানী.oga|''Shopnoshondhānī''}}) is a Bengali theater group from [[Kolkata]]. The group was founded on 29 May 1992.<ref name="wordpress1"/> Swapnasandhani has been marked by the acting and direction of [[Kaushik Sen]]. In November 2017, Sen stopped directing the group in order to bring change and "explore the creativity of the group".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bengali/movies/news/kaushik-sen-quits-debesh-takes-over-theatre-group/articleshow/61796070.cms|title=Kaushik Sen quits, Debesh takes over theatre group | newspaper=The Times of India|date=25 November 2017 | first=Shamayita | last=Chakraborty | accessdate=29 May 2018 }}</ref>
==Performance== From 2006, Swapnasandhani began performing on a regular basis at the [[Sujata Sadan]] every Saturday. This eliminated their need to wait in queue for free slots at the major theatres like the [[Academy of Fine Arts, Kolkata|Academy of Fine Arts]], [[Madhusudan Mancha]] etc.
==Major productions== <!--##################################################--> <!--# Add names in chronological order #--> <!--##################################################--> Till April, 2011 Swapnasandhani has staged 12 full-length plays and 14 short ones.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kaushik Sen Interview|url=http://calcuttatube.com/koushik-sen-on-bengali-theatre-swapnasandhani/147376/}}</ref> Some of those are: *Prachya. *Ajke Aamar Chhuti *Bhalo Rakshosher Golpo (2005). *Banku Babur Bandhu (2006). *Daakghar (2006). *Malyaban (2006). *Suprobhat (2006). *Dakghor (2007). *Hargoj (2008) based on a work of [[Bangladesh]]i writer Selim Al-Deen. *Bhoy (2009). *Darjiparar Marjinara (2009) written by [[Bratya Basu]], travels through the squalid rooms and alleys of Calcutta’s biggest red-light district Sonagachhi.<ref name="Way of all flesh">{{cite news|title=Way of all flesh|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1090528/jsp/entertainment/story_11027408.jsp|publisher=Way of all flesh|accessdate=14 May 2012|location=Calcutta, India|first=Mohua|last=Das|date=28 May 2009}}</ref> *Birpurush (2010) *Macbeth (2012) Bengali theatre based on [[William Shakespeare]]'s play [[Macbeth]].<ref name="‘Performance speaks louder than star power’">{{cite news|title=Performance speaks louder than star power|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-04-12/news-interviews/31330352_1_bangladeshi-swapnasandhani-bengal|accessdate=11 May 2012|newspaper=Times of India|date=12 April 2012<!--, 11.35AM IST-->}}</ref> *Thana Theke Aschi (2013) *Karkatkantir Deshe *Nirbhaya (2016) *Ashwathama (2017) *Taraye Taraye (2018) *1984 (2018)
==Celebrity appearance== *Bengali film and television actress [[Roopa Ganguly]] has acted with Swapnasandhani in the theatre ''Suprabhat'', which was based on a novel of [[Jibanananda Das]].<ref name="A rolling repertory Stage On & Off">{{cite news|title=A rolling repertory Stage On & Off|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1061104/asp/calcutta/story_6958118.asp|date=4 November 2006 | location=Calcutta, India|work=The Telegraph}}</ref> *Actress [[Arpita Pal]] acted in the theatre "Notir Pujo", which has been successful.<ref name="‘Performance speaks louder than star power’"/> *Television stars Debdut Ghosh and [[Rajatava Dutta]] have acted in "Shei Sumouli"<ref name="‘Performance speaks louder than star power’"/> *Actor [[Kanchan Mullick]] has acted in theatre ''Darjiparar Marjinara'', written by [[Bratya Basu]].<ref name="Thursday , May 28, 2009">{{cite news|title=Thursday , May 28, 2009|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1090528/jsp/entertainment/story_11027408.jsp|accessdate=11 May 2012|newspaper=Telegraph|date=28 May 2009|location=Calcutta, India|first=Mohua|last=Das}}</ref>
